    answer: 'The AAP and American Academy of Sleep Medicine recommend 8 to 10 hours of sleep per 24 hours for teens ages 13 to 18 (AAP, 2014). Most teens get 6 to 7 hours on school nights due to early school start times, academic pressure, extracurriculars, and biology — a real sleep deficit with documented effects on mood, cognitive performance, and physical health. The AAP advocates for high schools to start no earlier than 8:30 AM.',
  },
